					<marginalia_text>
						Dicens dic melius: fac melius faciens.
						Axiophilus in Ode 3. Mercurij sublimati.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Axiophilus"/>
					<person name="Mercury"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Ars iuuenis: virtus vir: Furor ipse, deus. in
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						eade[m] Ode.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				While speaking, speak better; do better, while doing.
				Axiophilus in the Third Ode of elevated Mercury. <!-- CG: I'm not entirely sure what this Ode 3 is. --> <!--JG: Me neither. One of Horace's Odes is addressed to Mercury, but this is Ode X. Have to ask a specialist-->
				Art is a youth; virtue a man; fury itself, god. In the same Ode.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
